Load-bearing risks / open questions:

Cross-surface identity continuity at multi-user scale is untested. This is the load-bearing assumption from the Ambient Turn document; Stage 5 is where it gets validated or falsified.
The economics of running per-user 70B+-class Prime models are unknown. Stage 2's viability proof addresses part of this, but at-scale cloud economics is a Stage 5 discovery.
Trust and privacy with always-on sensing scales from single-user (Max) to many-user in ways that need substantial architecture. This is a Stage 5 surface, not a Stage 3 one, but the design propagates.
Onboarding quality determines productization success. If Cold Start doesn't make Helm feel meaningfully personal from first engagement, the product fails regardless of the cognitive architecture beneath it. This is a UX-research-heavy stage.


4. Productization (Fine Sketch)

The path from Max-only to many-Max-shaped Helms, lightly sketched.

This section captures the pieces we have agreed to preserve without full-speccing them. Stage 5 will produce the complete architecture; this section is the shared memory of what we intend.
Cold Start
The onboarding flow for a new user meeting Helm for the first time. Elements, in rough sequence:

Structured belief-extracting questions — not a survey, a conversation. Helm asks things designed to reveal the user's working style, priorities, and relationships. Extraction is happening; the experience is conversational.
Mirror moment — at a key point in onboarding, Helm reflects a portrait back to the user: "Here is what I think I am understanding about you." The user corrects. This is the first calibration pass.
First-win output — Helm produces something immediately valuable in the user's world, based on what he's learned so far. Proof of utility within the first session.
Background integration scan — with permission, Helm reaches into connected systems (email, calendar, etc.) to build initial context. Happens alongside the onboarding conversation, not after.
Portable onboarding via import — users can import their own context (belief summaries, preference files) from prior systems or from earlier Helm interactions.
Observed preference mechanism — Helm notices preferences the user didn't explicitly state and incorporates them. "You keep preferring short summaries; I'll default to that."

Tiered presence as user permission
At productization, tier becomes a setting the user controls:

Async (T1-equivalent) — Helm responds when engaged, doesn't initiate
Scheduled (T2-equivalent) — Helm runs on rhythms the user configures
Present (T3-equivalent) — Helm is always on, with ambient awareness

The user chooses. They can change their mind. The framework supports fluid adjustment.
Identity at scale
Per-user brains. Each user gets their own Supabase project (or equivalent isolated datastore). Data isolation is architectural, not access-controlled-in-a-shared-database. This is load-bearing and untested at scale.
Monetization
Deliberately not detailed. This roadmap is not a pricing or market document. Stage 5 planning will include monetization architecture. Framework question: is the monetization model per-user subscription, compute-pass-through, tiered-by-presence-level, or something else? Undecided; flagged for Stage 5.

